" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 287 2 "kp" 
}{TEXT -1 70 "  Is there a way to just print the prime numbers and not
 all the rest?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 404 "N.B.  There are various questions and properties about p
rime numbers which are of interest and study.  For example, it is know
n that there are infinitely many primes.  There is only one even prime
. (Why?)  The distribution of the odd primes is not fully understood. \+
 If two consecutive odd numbers are both prime (e.g., (5,7) ; (17,19),
 (101,103)), then such a pair of consecutive odd primes is called a " 
}{TEXT 282 19 "pair of twin primes" }{TEXT -1 174 ".  It is not known \+
whether or not there are infinitely many such pairs of twin primes.  I
t is known that there can be arbitrarily large gaps between consecutiv
e primes.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 372 "5.  Relatively Prime Numbers.  Two positive integers are
 said to be relatively prime if the only positive integer which (evenl
y) divides both of them is 1.  Examples of  (pairs of) relatively prim
e integers are:  74, 51;   13, 120;   344280, 267317.  If two integers
 are relatively prime, then the greatest common divisor of the two int
egers must be 1.  The maple command " }{TEXT 278 3 "gcd" }{TEXT -1 
296 " can be used to determine whether greatest common divisor of two \+
integers is 1, i.e., whether the two integers are relatively prime.  S
how that each of the above mentioned pairs of integers are relatively \+
prime.  Find three other pairs of relatively prime integers with the f
ollowing constraints:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 72 "(a) neither inte
ger is itself prime; (b) each integer is more than 1000." }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "gcd(7
4,51);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
