F(6#F+F0F,-F(6#\"\"(F,)-F(6#\"#6F0F," }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 289 2 "kp" }{TEXT -1 14 "  Okay to here" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 11 "You assig
n " }{TEXT 272 2 "x " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 273 1 "y" }{TEXT -1 
88 " to be any pair of numbers (positive integers).  Execute the follo
wing command sequence:" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "x \+
:= ;\ny := ;" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "x=ifactor(x
);\ny=ifactor(y);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "x*y=if
actor(x*y);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "gcd(x,y)=ifa
ctor(gcd(x,y));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "lcm(x,y)
=ifactor(lcm(x,y));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 45 "lcm(
x,y)*gcd(x,y)=ifactor(lcm(x,y)*gcd(x,y));" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }{TEXT 271 97 "What was the co
mmon theme of the above three sets of calculations for different pairs
 of numbers?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 147 "Use the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic to provide a written
 argument to verify the general formula that for any pair of positive \+
integers (m,n):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 34 "         mn = gcd(m,n) * lcm(m,n)." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 274 9 "Argument:" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 198 "8.   Numerical Appr
oximations.  While Maple can perform exact arithmetic, there are times
 when it is important or helpful to obtain a decimal approximation for
 some exact answer.  For instance, the " }{TEXT 275 5 "solve" }{TEXT 
-1 66 " command can be used to find the \"exact\" roots of the polynom
ial  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p := x^3-11*x^2-70*x+600;" "6#>%\"pG,**$%\"xG\"
\"$\"\"\"*&\"#6F)*$F'\"\"#F)!\"\"*&\"#qF)F'F)F.\"$+'F)" }{TEXT -1 34 "
 .  Execute the following command:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 43 "roots_of_p := solve(x^3-11*x
^2-70*x+600,x);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 289 "That isn't very illuminating.  It maybe hard to tell, bu
t there are three roots.  If you change the problem slightly, it may b
e even harder.  (For example, change the number 70 in the above proble
m to 80 and then do the calculation!)  To display each root separately
, execute the commands:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 24 "r1 := Re(roots_of_p[1]);" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 24 "r2 := Re(roots_of_p[2]);" }}
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 24 "r3 := Re(roots_of_p[3]);" }
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 47 "Even th
at isn't all that helpful.  The command " }{TEXT 276 5 "evalf" }{TEXT 
-1 187 "  which stands for \"evaluate using floating point\" can be us
ed to give a decimal approximation of an value.  The number of decimal
 places can be specified.  Execute the following command:" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "evalf
(r1);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "evalf(r2);" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "evalf(r3);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 98 "With these last comput
ations,  we at least have a feel for the general location of the roots
 of p." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
199 "To obtain a feel for what \"floating point arithmetic\" means, ex
ecute the following command sequence and record any relevant observati
ons about what the commands do, automatic features of Maple, etc. " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 6 "1+2/3;" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "evalf(%);" }}
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 12 "1/2+1/3+1/4;" }}}{EXCHG 
